Why OOP?
Problem Before OOP
In procedural programming, data and functions are separate.
Example:
String customerName;
double balance;

deposit();
withdraw();

As software grows:

Code becomes difficult to manage
Data can be modified from anywhere
Reusability decreases
Maintenance becomes difficult
OOP Solution

Object-Oriented Programming organizes software around objects.

An object contains:

Data + Behavior

Instead of thinking about functions first, OOP models real-world entities.

Examples:

Real World                    Software Object
Student                      	Student Object
Car	                          Car Object
Bank Account	                BankAccount Object
Employee	                    Employee Object
Product	                      Product Object

Benefits of OOP: 
1.Better code organization
2.Reusability
3.Scalability
4.Maintainability
5.Security
6.Real-world modeling

Class:  A class is a blueprint/template used to create objects.

A class defines:

Attributes (state)
Methods (behavior)

Example
class Student {

    String name;
    int age;

    void study() {
        System.out.println("Studying");
    }
}

Important Point

A class itself does not create memory for actual data.

It is only a design.

Real World Analogy

Blueprint of a house.

A blueprint is not an actual house.

Similarly:

class Car

is not an actual car.

Object
Definition

An object is an instance of a class.

Example
Student s1 = new Student();

Now an actual student object exists.

Every Object Has
1. State

Properties

Example:

Name = Sai
Age = 22

2. Behavior

Actions

Study()
Sleep()
AttendClass()
3. Identity

Every object has a unique existence.

Example:

Student s1 = new Student();
Student s2 = new Student();

Both are different objects.

Memory View
Student s1 = new Student();

Reference Variable:

s1

stored in Stack.

Object:

Student Object

stored in Heap.

Constructor : A constructor is a special member automatically invoked when an object is created.

Purpose:
1.Initialize object state
2.Ensure object starts with valid data
3.Characteristics
4.Same name as class
5.No return type
6.Automatically executed
7.Can be overloaded

Example
class Student {

    Student() {
        System.out.println("Object Created");
    }
}
Student s1 = new Student();

Output:

Object Created

Why Constructors Exist ???

Without constructor:

Student s1 = new Student();

s1.name = "Sai";
s1.age = 22;

Programmer may forget initialization.

Constructor forces initialization.

Parameterized Constructor
class Student {

    String name;

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

Usage:

Student s1 = new Student("Sai");
Constructor Overloading

Multiple constructors with different parameters.

Student() {}

Student(String name) {}

Student(String name, int age) {}

Used for flexible object creation.

Default Constructor

If no constructor is written:

class Student {}

Java automatically provides:

Student() {}

called Default Constructor.

Important:

If you create any constructor manually:

Student(String name) {}

Java stops creating the default constructor.


this Keyword : this refers to the current object.

Variable Ambiguity

Example:

class Student {

    String name;

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

Left side:  this.name

Current object's variable.

Right side: name

Constructor parameter.

Meaning:
Store parameter value inside current object's variable.
Visualization

Before Constructor:

Object

name = null

Constructor Call:

new Student("Sai");

Execution:

this.name = name;

After:

Object

name = Sai
Constructor Chaining

Example:

class Student {

    Student() {
        this("Sai");
        System.out.println("Default");
    }

    Student(String name) {
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

Execution:

new Student();

Output:

Sai
Default

Reason:

Default constructor runs
Calls parameterized constructor
Parameterized constructor finishes
Control returns
Remaining code executes
Uses of this
Access Current Object Variable
this.name
Call Current Method
this.display();
Call Another Constructor
this("Sai");

Must be first statement.

Encapsulation
Definition

Encapsulation is the process of hiding internal data and exposing controlled access through methods.

Goal

Protect object state.

Without Encapsulation
class BankAccount {

    double balance;
}

Anyone can write:

account.balance = -10000;

Unsafe.

With Encapsulation
class BankAccount {

    private double balance;

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        balance += amount;
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}

Now balance is protected.

Benefits
Security

Prevents unauthorized modification.

Validation

Rules can be enforced.

Example:

if(amount > 0)
Maintainability

Internal implementation can change.

Outside code remains unchanged.

Real World Examples
ATM

